Flights dataset Exploration¶

by Ahmed Mohammed Mohammed¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

The data set keeps record of the fligths info in the US airports in the period from 2010 to 2020. It contains detailed information about the number of flights delayed, time delayed, reasons for delays and the contribution of each reason. It also keeps record of the canceled and diverted flights in each month for each airport and carrier.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The data set contains 21 columns and 165190 rows. It records the year,month ,airports names and codes, carriers names and codes. For each flight described by the previous features the number of flights is recorded in each month (arr_flights).The number of flghts delayed by more than 15 minutes (arr_delay15) is recorded in each month and the contribution of the different factors in the number of delayed flights, and time of delation in minutes are recorded. The factors are severe weather conditions, carrier problems, security, late aircraft (aircrafts that have a flight right after another flight) or National Air System delays (NAS).

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The airports and carriers performance across years and months in each year.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I think that the number of flights cancelled, diverted, delayed across the months will be the major important features. Also the delation time that is independent of weather and NAS delays (airport and carriers delays) will be important too.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

There were outliers in the number of flights arrived which caused outliers in the number of cancelled flights and high numbers in other columns. The year 2020 had unusual situations that made more unusual records due to Covid-19 pandemic and these records were removed. The log scale was necessary in the investigation as there were long tails in the histograms.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

There wasn't unusual distribution particularly. The diverted flights had a very small number of unique values (180). Most of the records were at 0. Non zero values were mostly between 0 and 5 so divertion is considered a rare thing to happen and willn't help us in our farther invesigation. I removed arrived flights outliers and year 2020. I also removed the nulls at the first as there were a very small number of rows (which each has most its values as nulls) compared to the data set size.

def plot_log(x,**kwargs):
    labels = [1,3,10,30,100,300,1000,3000,10000,30000]
    
    step = 0.1
    nbins = 10**np.arange(0,np.log10(x.max())+step,step)
    plt.hist(x,bins=nbins)
    plt.xscale('log')
    
    plt.xticks(labels,labels)

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

Human contribution in dealyed flights in the best 5 carriers looks to be associated with the number of flights each carrier holds. Two carriers are improving with time. They got a bigger number of flights and the lower human delation contribution. The carriers are the Delta Air Lines Inc. (DL) and the SkyWest Airlines Inc. (OO). Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

The biggest carrier doesn't have a main airport but alternatively it has relative above moderate number of flights in a lot of airports. However the second bigger carrier which has a very low human delation contribution is relying on one airport heavily. The relation between the dependency on one airport and human delation looks to be negative.
